    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1949-03-31T07:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1949-03-31T07:00:00-05:00" n="137"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d137">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">
                    <gloss target="#t_ECA1">ECA</gloss> Telegram Files, FRC Acc. No. 53A278,</note>
                <note rend="inline" type="source">Paris <gloss target="#t_Repto1">Repto</gloss>,
                    Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Acting United States Special Representative in Europe
                        Under the Economic Assistance Act of 1948</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Katz</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the Administrator for Economic
                        Cooperation</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Hoffman</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">secret</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Paris</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1949-03-31T13:00:00+01:00"
                            >March 31, 1949—1 p. m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <gloss target="#t_Repto1">Repto</gloss> 3407. For Hoffman for <gloss
                        target="#t_FACC1">FACC</gloss>. <gloss target="#t_OSR1">OSR</gloss> report
                    on impact on <gloss target="#t_ERP1">ERP</gloss> of proposed military assistance
                    program to Western Union countries finished today and being pouched
                        soonest.<note n="1" xml:id="d137fn1">Not found in Department of State
                        files.</note> Important conclusions as follows: <list>
                        <label>1.</label>
                        <item>Proposed military assistance program would not jeopardize <gloss
                                target="#t_ERP1">ERP</gloss>. On contrary, <gloss target="#t_MAP1"
                                >MAP</gloss> will be important factor in developing level of
                            confidence in future Western Europe necessary to insure continuing
                            viability beyond end <gloss target="#t_ERP1">ERP</gloss> in 1952.</item>
                        <label>2.</label>
                        <item>Physical capacity for proposed additional production available. This
                            production probably too small to cause serious diversion manufacturing
                            facilities, labor, fuel and energy from recovery program. Electrical
                            energy tight in continental Western Europe and requires better survey
                            for complete answer, but believe problem manageable.</item>
                        <label>3.</label>
                        <item>Since amount dollar aid for 49/50 requested by <gloss target="#t_ECA1"
                                >ECA</gloss> minimum necessary for satisfactory rate economic
                            recovery Western Europe, any dollars required by Western Union countries
                            for necessary dollar costs of imports raw materials, machinery etc.,
                            under <gloss target="#t_MAP1">MAP</gloss> should be <pb facs="0272"
                                n="258" xml:id="pg_258"/> met through additional amounts of dollar
                            aid. Available data indicate suggested 100 million to 150 million
                            dollars sufficient for fiscal year ’50.</item>
                        <label>4.</label>
                        <item>Burden increased military production on Western Union countries
                            national budgets is of manageable proportions, but will call for some
                            additional sacrifice, probably new taxes. See clause (<hi rend="italic"
                                >a</hi>) of paragraph 5, below.</item>
                        <label>5.</label>
                        <item>Following three elements of <gloss target="#t_MAP1">MAP</gloss>
                            require careful attention now and in future. <list>
                                <label>(<hi rend="italic">a</hi>)</label>
                                <item>Financial situation in Western Union countries still critical
                                    so imperative increases in military expenditures must be met
                                    from noninflationary sources.</item>
                                <label>(<hi rend="italic">b</hi>)</label>
                                <item>Financial arrangements for transfer European produced military
                                    equipment under <gloss target="#t_MAP1">MAP</gloss> for first
                                    year should be made outside <gloss target="#t_OEEC1"
                                        >OEEC</gloss> intra-European payments plan on <hi
                                        rend="italic">ad hoc</hi> basis.</item>
                                <label>(<hi rend="italic">c</hi>)</label>
                                <item>After initial allocation of spare parts for American equipment
                                    transferred to Europe is expended, there will be continuing
                                    requirement for spare parts involving either substantial dollar
                                    drain on Western Union countries, or development European
                                    production almost from scratch, which will not be easy.</item>
                            </list>
                        </item>
                    </list>
                </p>
                <p>Sent Washington <gloss target="#t_Repto1">Repto</gloss> 3407; repeated London
                        <gloss target="#t_Repto1">Repto</gloss> 432 for Finletter and Douglas;
                    Brussels <gloss target="#t_Repto1">Repto</gloss> 167 for Blaine<note n="2"
                        xml:id="d137fn2">James G. Blaine, Chief of the <gloss target="#t_ECA1"
                            >ECA</gloss> Mission in Belgium.</note> and Kirk; Hague <gloss
                        target="#t_Repto1">Repto</gloss> 175 for Valentine<note n="3"
                        xml:id="d137fn3">Alan Valentine, Chief of the <gloss target="#t_ECA1"
                            >ECA</gloss> Mission in the Netherlands.</note> and Baruch (please show
                    Harriman upon arrival).</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Katz</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
